@Mereologist It isn't worth arguing about.  "Playing God" was not Shelley's theme.  Perhaps going against the natural order was.  There are claims that Galvani was an influence, but there is no real sign of that in the creature's creation (the electricity and the dead bodies are both later additions in adaptations).  Likewise E Darwin is named an influence but there is no specific sign of that.  Lind may have been a general influence, but it seems really that the discussions she was involved in with Percy and friends about the origin of life may have more been her main influence.   I had read something from her regarding Victor usurping a woman's creative domain, but I cannot recall it off the top of my head and need to go looking.  
Shelley was a feminist, but a feminist of her day. Not of her mother's day, and certainly not of our day.

Interestingly (at least to me) in my first re-read for many years I am struck with the simplicity of the plot and characters and the complexity of the narrative and dialogues.   This could well have been the equivalent of Young Adult fiction.  That isn't a criticism, just a recognition, and I keep in mind that Shelley was only 18 when she started writing this.

